President Obama was briefed by Assistant to the President for Homeland Security John Brennan on the response efforts to the severe weather and flooding in Tennessee and other southeastern states. The federal government, through FEMA, has been working with state and local officials since the weekend. FEMA Administrator Craig Fugate will be visiting Tennessee to view the damage, meet with officials, and receive briefings on the response efforts. This is his second trip to the state. The President has been in contact with Governor Bredesen and other governors in affected states. FEMA representatives are also on the ground in Kentucky, Mississippi, Arkansas, and Louisiana to assess damages and determine any additional federal resources needed. The President requested ongoing updates on the situation and for the federal government to respond swiftly to any requests for assistance.